definition.value: A monovalent inorganic anion obtained by deprotonation of one of the two OH groups in phosphonic acid.
A monovalent inorganic anion obtained by deprotonation of one of the two OH groups in diphosphoniic acid.

A benzimidazolecarboxylic acid that is 1H-benzimidazole-7-carboxylic acid substituted by an ethoxy group at position 2 and a ({2'-(1H-tetrazol-5-yl)[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-yl}methyl) group at position 1. It is a angiotensin receptor antagonist used for the treatment of hypertension.
A heterocyclyl group derived from a heteroarene by removal of a hydrogen atom from any ring atom.
A bivalent group formed by removing two hydrogen atoms from a hydrocarbon, the free valencies of which are not engaged in a double bond.
A divalent group, R2C=, formed by removing two hydrogen atoms from the same carbon atom of a hydrocarbon, the free valencies of which are engaged in a double bond.
Trivalent groups, RC#, formed by removing three hydrogen atoms from the same carbon atom of a hydrocarbon, the free valencies of which are engaged in a triple bond.
The vinyl or ethenyl group (CH2=CH-) and derivatives formed by substitution.
An organyl derivative of the silyl group, R3Si-.

A 38-membered ring lactone containing seven (E)-double bonds between positions 22 and 35 and substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 9, 11, 13, 17 and 19, oxo groups at positions 3, 7 and 15, a carboxy group at position 18, a 3-amino-3,6-dideoxymannopyranosyloxy group at position 21, a methyl group at position 36 and a 7-(4-aminophenyl)-5-hydroxy-4-methyl-7-oxoheptan-2-yl group at position 37. It is the major component of candicidin, a mixture of antifungal heptaene macrolides obtained from a strain of Streptomyces griseus.
A nucleosidyl group is a group formed by loss of OH from a nucleoside molecule.
A molecular entity containing one or more atoms of a transition element.
An adenosyl group is a group formed by loss of a 2'-, 3'- or 5'-hydroxy group from the ribose moiety of adenosine.
Dioxo carboxylic acids formally derived from aldoses by replacement of two secondary CHOH groups by carbonyl groups.
A trionic acid that consists of propionic acid substituted at positions 2 and 3 by hydroxy groups.
